But DTR suggests the system is non-Markovian.

18:44.340 --> 18:45.480
It has a memory.

18:45.960 --> 18:47.540
It remembers its past states.

18:47.940 --> 18:51.920
So the entropy that's stored in one of those volts doesn't just act instantly.

18:52.340 --> 18:56.080
It acts through what the paper calls a memory kernel.

18:56.960 --> 19:01.920
The energy stored in an entropy vault might not be released immediately when the conditions are right.

19:02.080 --> 19:05.080
It can be held back, buffered for a period of time.

19:05.080 --> 19:10.420
This creates a time lag, or what engineers would call hysteresis in the system.

19:10.740 --> 19:11.520
And why is that important?

19:11.640 --> 19:13.580
What does adding a delay do?

19:13.840 --> 19:14.880
Because it creates rhythms.

19:15.060 --> 19:16.200
It creates oscillations.

19:16.300 --> 19:19.680
If everything happened instantly, you just get one big flash and that's it.

19:20.100 --> 19:22.400
But with delays, you can get cycles.

19:22.600 --> 19:24.040
You get pulses of creation.

19:24.220 --> 19:26.620
It allows the universe to breathe, to have a cadence.

19:26.980 --> 19:29.460
Okay, so DTR provides the timing and the rhythm.

19:30.160 --> 19:30.840
Engine 3.

19:32.120 --> 19:32.560
PTLR.

19:32.920 --> 19:33.520
This is a mouthful.

19:33.520 --> 19:37.080
Poincaré triggered lattice recrystallization.

19:37.660 --> 19:43.340
It is, but it's absolutely crucial for propping up the whole static universe argument.

19:43.540 --> 19:45.620
It's the engine that recharges the battery.

19:45.760 --> 19:47.500
Lattice and recrystallization.

19:47.860 --> 19:50.980
That implies a grid, a crystal structure.

19:51.840 --> 19:53.640
Are we back to living in a simulation?

19:54.160 --> 20:00.140
Not necessarily a simulation in the pop culture sense, but it does suggest a discrete reality.

20:00.140 --> 20:05.480
The paper posits that the plenum isn't infinitely smooth at the smallest scales.

20:05.820 --> 20:07.180
It's pixelated.

20:07.400 --> 20:11.260
It has a fundamental lattice spacing, which they call dollars.

20:11.420 --> 20:13.120
Okay, so space is a grid.

20:13.520 --> 20:14.200
A crystal.

20:14.380 --> 20:15.940
A crystal plenum, yes.

20:16.360 --> 20:20.820
And this brings in the brilliant French mathematician Henri Poincaré.

20:20.820 --> 20:25.880
He proved a theorem back in the 19th century called Poincaré recurrence.

20:26.040 --> 20:27.080
I think I remember this one.

20:27.080 --> 20:32.700
In simple terms, it says that if you have a closed system, like our finite, compact box of a universe,

20:33.260 --> 20:36.900
with a finite number of possible states, the pixels on the grid,

20:37.160 --> 20:42.100
then eventually the system must return to a state that is arbitrarily close to its initial state.

20:42.160 --> 20:43.400
History repeats itself.

20:43.640 --> 20:44.000
Literally.

20:44.460 --> 20:45.600
Mathematically, yes.

20:46.080 --> 20:51.900
Given enough time, the atoms in this room will spontaneously arrange themselves back to the way they were an hour ago.

20:52.320 --> 20:54.800
The timescales are just astronomically long.

20:54.940 --> 20:55.140
Okay.

20:55.440 --> 20:58.660
Fliction argues that this recurrence is what charges the batteries.

20:59.400 --> 21:03.140
As the system cycles through its vast but finite number of states,

21:03.140 --> 21:08.840
it naturally re-concentrates entropy in certain areas just by random chance over eons.

21:09.440 --> 21:11.140
It rebuilds the entropy vaults.

21:11.140 --> 21:14.080
So the PTLR engine is the battery charger.

21:14.780 --> 21:19.620
It takes the dissipated, used-up entropy and, through these recurrence cycles,

21:19.820 --> 21:22.500
gathers it back together into the vaults for the next round.

21:22.740 --> 21:23.160
Exactly.

21:23.540 --> 21:26.240
It creates the preconditions for eruption.

21:26.820 --> 21:30.780
Without the lattice and the recurrence theorem, the universe would run out of juice.

21:31.000 --> 21:33.180
It would have one burst of creation and then die.

21:33.820 --> 21:38.380
With PTLR, it's a self-renewing, perpetual motion machine of creation.

21:38.380 --> 21:44.760
Okay, so to recap, PTLR charges the battery, DTR sets the timer for when the battery goes off.

21:44.900 --> 21:48.920
And engine 4, S-I-E-D, the scalar eruption, is the spark.

21:49.080 --> 21:50.840
It's the actual release of that energy.

21:51.020 --> 21:56.960
Which leaves engine 5, and this is the one that really got me, NFR, the neutrino fossil registry.

21:57.220 --> 21:59.060
This is the one that keeps me up at night.

21:59.280 --> 21:59.460
Yeah.

21:59.600 --> 22:00.680
It's a wild idea.

22:01.180 --> 22:02.040
Fossil registry.

22:02.040 --> 22:05.020
It implies a record is being kept.

22:05.860 --> 22:08.660
The paper has to address a very serious problem.

22:09.480 --> 22:13.300
In a closed, static box, where does the information go?

22:13.540 --> 22:14.820
Where does the waste heat go?

22:15.340 --> 22:20.840
In the Big Bang model, information and energy eventually leave our observable horizon.

22:21.700 --> 22:24.440
They are, for all practical purposes, lost to us.

22:24.500 --> 22:26.400
But here, nothing can leave the box.

22:26.400 --> 22:28.640
So doesn't the box just fill up with clutter?

22:29.180 --> 22:30.040
With waste heat?

22:30.520 --> 22:32.660
Does it not just fry itself over time?

22:32.840 --> 22:34.000
That seems like a big problem.

22:34.400 --> 22:36.480
The NFR is the proposed solution.

22:36.920 --> 22:40.960
It suggests the box creates a library, not just a junkyard.

22:41.520 --> 22:45.020
The paper claims that the residue of every single eruption,

22:45.700 --> 22:49.920
the thermodynamic cost of creating a star, the information of its formation,

22:50.260 --> 22:53.080
is encoded into weakly interacting fields.

22:53.620 --> 22:55.780
Specifically, the neutrino background.

22:55.780 --> 22:57.760
Neutrinos, the ghost particles.

22:57.920 --> 23:01.160
They can pass through light years of lead without hitting a single atom.

23:01.400 --> 23:03.660
Which makes them the perfect storage medium.

23:04.280 --> 23:05.900
Because they interact so rarely,

23:06.400 --> 23:09.420
the information they carry doesn't get corrupted or degraded.

23:10.240 --> 23:12.640
Fliction suggests that the cosmic neutrino background

23:12.640 --> 23:15.040
isn't just random noise from the Big Bang.

23:15.380 --> 23:17.920
It's a fossilized entropy trace.

23:17.920 --> 23:22.600
So every star, every galaxy, every structure that has ever existed

23:22.600 --> 23:26.140
in the entire history of this timeless plenum

23:26.140 --> 23:30.820
has left a permanent signature, a ghost, in the neutrino field.

23:31.060 --> 23:33.260
A memory operator is the term they use.

23:33.740 --> 23:36.380
It suggests that if you could build a detector sensitive enough

23:36.380 --> 23:40.120
to read the precise state of the neutrino background with incredible precision,

23:40.380 --> 23:44.220
you could reconstruct the 4D history of the entire cosmos.

23:44.220 --> 23:46.460
That is a staggering thought.

23:46.640 --> 23:48.760
The universe is a self-recording hard drive

23:48.760 --> 23:50.520
and we're just swimming through the data.

23:50.680 --> 23:52.680
It creates a perfect closed loop.

23:53.340 --> 23:56.020
Smoothing, GAS, cleans things up.

23:56.240 --> 23:59.080
Recurrence, PTLR, gathers the fuel.

23:59.560 --> 24:01.520
Memory, DTR, sets the timing.

24:01.800 --> 24:04.580
Eruption, SIED, creates the structure.

24:05.080 --> 24:07.640
And the registry, NFR, records the history.

24:07.820 --> 24:10.020
It's a perfect perpetual machine.

24:10.360 --> 24:10.800
But.

24:11.160 --> 24:14.160
And okay, here is the but I've been holding back this whole time.

24:14.180 --> 24:15.100
I knew it was coming.

24:15.200 --> 24:16.260
The elephant in the room.

24:16.640 --> 24:19.440
You can build a beautiful machine in the world of equations.

24:19.920 --> 24:21.820
It can be elegant and self-consistent.

24:22.340 --> 24:24.860
But at some point, we have to look out the window.

24:25.360 --> 24:27.700
And when we look out the window, we see redshift.

24:27.960 --> 24:31.080
We see that every distant galaxy is moving away from us.

24:31.360 --> 24:35.000
And the further away they are, the faster they appear to move.

24:35.940 --> 24:38.300
Edwin Hubble discovered this 100 years ago.

24:38.300 --> 24:42.360
It is the bedrock of modern observational cosmology.

24:43.440 --> 24:47.000
How can Fliction possibly explain redshift in a static box?

24:47.520 --> 24:50.780
This is, without a doubt, the most controversial part of the paper.

24:51.340 --> 24:54.600
It's in Section 5, Implications and Observables.

24:55.360 --> 24:59.340
And Fliction knows this is the hill their theory has to climb or die on.

24:59.560 --> 25:03.040
They directly challenged the Doppler interpretation of redshift.

25:03.200 --> 25:05.340
The Doppler effect is pretty basic physics, though.

25:05.340 --> 25:08.260
A train moves away from you, its whistles pitch drops.

25:08.620 --> 25:12.060
A galaxy moves away from you, its lights color drops, it redshifts.

25:12.540 --> 25:17.260
It is basic physics if the object is actually moving through space or if the space between

25:17.260 --> 25:18.440
you and it is expanding.

25:18.940 --> 25:24.080
But Fliction argues for a third possibility, an acoustic signature mechanism.

25:24.220 --> 25:24.720
Acoustic.

25:24.820 --> 25:26.840
You mean sound, like sound waves in space.

25:27.200 --> 25:27.780
In a sense.

25:27.900 --> 25:29.100
Remember, this isn't a vacuum.

25:29.240 --> 25:29.860
It's a plenum.

25:30.080 --> 25:30.820
It's a medium.

25:31.120 --> 25:31.740
A substance.

25:31.740 --> 25:38.660
When an eruption happens, when a galaxy bursts forth, it sends shockwaves ripples through

25:38.660 --> 25:40.780
the scalar field and the entropy field.

25:41.020 --> 25:42.500
Like dropping a stone in a pond.

25:42.640 --> 25:43.180
Exactly.

25:43.620 --> 25:47.800
Now, imagine billions of stones being dropped all over the pond for eons.

25:48.200 --> 25:50.400
The entire plenum is vibrating.

25:50.580 --> 25:52.960
It's humming with the energy of creation.

25:52.960 --> 26:00.120
The paper argues that light traveling through this vibrating, high-entropy medium loses energy

26:00.120 --> 26:04.760
over vast distances via a process they call internal redistribution.

26:05.160 --> 26:07.380
So the light gets tired as it travels.

26:07.600 --> 26:08.540
That's an old theory.

26:08.700 --> 26:09.220
Tired light.

26:09.420 --> 26:14.120
I thought that was debunked decades ago because any scattering process that makes light lose

26:14.120 --> 26:17.300
energy would also blur the images of distant galaxies.

26:17.440 --> 26:18.180
And we don't see that.

26:18.240 --> 26:19.060
They're perfectly sharp.

26:19.060 --> 26:22.300
And fliction anticipates the tired light critique.

26:22.800 --> 26:27.340
They're very clear that this isn't a random scattering process, which would cause blurring.

26:27.540 --> 26:33.860
They argue it's a coherent lattice interaction because the universe is a crystal, a grid.

26:34.500 --> 26:37.300
The energy loss is quantized and directional.

26:37.440 --> 26:38.180
It's not random.

26:38.560 --> 26:44.440
And it perfectly mimics the mathematical signature of a recession velocity, that linear relationship

26:44.440 --> 26:48.040
with distance without any actual recession.

26:48.040 --> 26:52.080
That is a very, very fine needle to thread, argument-wise.

26:52.120 --> 26:52.620
It is.

26:52.700 --> 26:53.760
It's a huge claim.

26:54.240 --> 26:59.440
But they try to bolster it by pointing to another major piece of cosmological evidence,

27:00.120 --> 27:03.200
Baryon acoustic oscillations, or BAO.

27:03.320 --> 27:03.780
Right, the BAO.

27:04.400 --> 27:04.580
Yeah.

27:04.640 --> 27:09.140
These are the giant rings or bubbles of galaxies we see in large-scale surveys.

27:09.620 --> 27:14.800
In standard cosmology, these are leftover sound waves from the plasma of the very early universe.

27:15.220 --> 27:17.400
They're like a standard ruler printed on the cosmos.

27:17.400 --> 27:18.880
That's the standard interpretation.

27:19.200 --> 27:25.200
Fliction, however, shows that their five-engine system naturally produces what they call quasi-periodic

27:25.200 --> 27:28.960
structure formation that looks exactly like the BAO data.

27:29.180 --> 27:32.640
So the rings of galaxies we see aren't echoes of the Big Bang.

27:33.280 --> 27:36.760
They are their resonance patterns of the vibrating plenum.

27:36.760 --> 27:38.420
Like Kladni figures.

27:38.640 --> 27:42.960
You know when you sprinkle sand on a metal plate and vibrate it with a violin bow?

27:43.520 --> 27:48.700
And the sand arranges itself into these beautiful, intricate geometric patterns?

27:49.040 --> 27:49.780
Yes, of course.

27:50.060 --> 27:53.260
Flix Slimshin is arguing the universe is a Kladni plate.

27:53.820 --> 27:57.900
The galaxies form at the nodes of the vibration, the quiet spots.

27:58.280 --> 28:02.180
And the voids are the antinodes, the places with high vibration.

28:02.180 --> 28:06.040
And the paper also mentions that the growth of structure is band-limited.

28:06.440 --> 28:09.460
Which directly supports the Kladni plate idea.

28:09.640 --> 28:12.160
You don't get structure at every possible size.

28:12.340 --> 28:15.980
You get distinct bands or preferred scales of structure.

28:16.220 --> 28:19.700
The size of galaxies, the size of clusters, the size of superclusters.

28:20.120 --> 28:20.800
It's harmonic.

28:21.220 --> 28:22.880
It has a musical quality to it.

28:22.940 --> 28:24.880
Okay, I'm starting to see the picture they're painting.

28:25.040 --> 28:26.120
It's not an explosion.

28:26.320 --> 28:26.940
It's a symphony.

28:27.380 --> 28:28.660
It's a resonating chamber.

28:28.660 --> 28:31.960
A symphony in a fixed, finite concert hall.

28:32.300 --> 28:32.620
Yes.

28:32.980 --> 28:35.500
But there is still one more layer to this onion.

28:36.420 --> 28:37.680
The deep theory section.

28:37.980 --> 28:39.060
I think it's section 17.

28:39.220 --> 28:43.440
It just drops this reference to the AKS-ZBV formulation.

28:43.900 --> 28:44.740
Ah, yes.

28:45.760 --> 28:47.100
Bottle and Vilkovisky.

28:47.360 --> 28:51.740
This is definitely for the hardcore physics and math listeners out there.

28:51.820 --> 28:54.600
I tried to read it, and I'll be honest, my eyes just crossed.

28:54.600 --> 29:00.040
Can you break it down, why do they need to bring in this incredibly high-level geometry?

29:00.400 --> 29:01.320
What does it add?

29:01.820 --> 29:03.160
It's about robustness.

29:03.680 --> 29:06.520
It's about proving that this isn't just a clever toy model.

29:07.300 --> 29:13.780
In modern physics, if you propose a new field or a new interaction, you have to prove it plays nicely with quantum field theory.

29:14.080 --> 29:16.100
You have to show it's gauge invariant.

29:16.520 --> 29:22.280
Which, in simple terms, means the physics doesn't break when you change your coordinate system or your point of view.

29:22.520 --> 29:23.300
Essentially, yes.

29:23.300 --> 29:31.240
The AKS-Z formulation is an incredibly powerful mathematical framework for handling these very complex, constrained systems.

29:31.520 --> 29:35.340
But the key takeaway from that section isn't really about the math itself.

29:35.820 --> 29:37.940
It's about the topological implications.

29:38.280 --> 29:38.840
Topology.

29:39.700 --> 29:43.100
The study of shapes that are preserved under stretching and bending.

29:43.640 --> 29:45.860
The donut and the coffee cup being the same thing.

29:45.940 --> 29:46.580
That's the one.

29:46.580 --> 29:53.280
The paper makes the argument that a scalar eruption fundamentally changes the homotopy type of the solution space.

29:53.720 --> 29:53.760
Okay.

29:53.900 --> 29:54.980
In English, what does that mean?

29:55.340 --> 29:55.480
Okay.

29:55.640 --> 30:00.520
Imagine you have a rubber band that is stretched around a tall, smooth cylinder.

30:01.000 --> 30:03.780
You can slide that rubber band up and down the cylinder.

30:04.020 --> 30:07.000
You can wiggle it, but you can't pop it off without breaking it.

30:07.360 --> 30:08.820
That's a topological constraint.

30:09.300 --> 30:11.640
Its state space is like a circle.

30:11.640 --> 30:13.060
Okay, I'm with you.

30:13.380 --> 30:20.460
Now imagine the cylinder suddenly, spontaneously, splits into two separate cylinders, standing side by side.

30:21.420 --> 30:23.640
The rubber band situation has fundamentally changed.

30:24.540 --> 30:25.880
It's not just in a new position.

30:26.220 --> 30:27.960
It's in a new kind of space.

30:28.620 --> 30:31.120
Its state space has a different shape.

30:31.400 --> 30:32.540
A different topology.

30:32.540 --> 30:36.200
The geometry of its possible existence has shifted.

30:36.440 --> 30:36.900
That's it.

30:37.300 --> 30:43.400
Flixian saying that an eruption, the formation of a star or a galaxy, isn't just matter moving around in space.

30:43.860 --> 30:47.360
It's a fundamental change in the connectedness of the vacuum itself.

30:48.160 --> 30:52.000
When a star forms, it punctures the topology of the Lamfrond state.

30:52.400 --> 30:54.900
It leaves behind a deep, geometric scar.

30:55.720 --> 30:59.860
This implies that matter and space are much more intertwined than we typically think.

31:00.560 --> 31:02.060
Matter isn't just sitting in space.

31:02.060 --> 31:03.760
It is a twisting of space.

31:03.960 --> 31:05.740
A change in its fundamental nature.

31:06.160 --> 31:10.620
Which brings us, in a very strange way, right back to Einstein.

31:11.720 --> 31:13.960
Matter tells spacetime how to curve.

31:14.600 --> 31:16.560
Spacetime tells matter how to move.

31:17.580 --> 31:21.080
Flixian is just rewriting the dictionary of how that conversation happens.

31:21.280 --> 31:22.980
It's not gravity and curvature.

31:23.300 --> 31:25.040
It's entropy and topology.

31:25.280 --> 31:26.880
It's a breathtaking proposal.

31:27.160 --> 31:29.680
I'm still stuck on the static part, though.

31:29.680 --> 31:35.520
It feels so claustrophobic compared to the infinite, expanding dark of the Big Bang.

31:35.640 --> 31:37.440
Or does it feel cozy?

31:37.700 --> 31:38.680
Does it feel like a home?

31:38.980 --> 31:40.660
That's one way to look at it, I suppose.

31:40.920 --> 31:43.500
Think about the philosophical shift for a moment.

31:43.500 --> 31:46.540
In the Big Bang model, we are debris.

31:47.260 --> 31:54.380
We are the shrapnel from a primordial explosion flying apart, getting colder and lonelier every single second.

31:54.460 --> 31:54.620
Right.

31:55.020 --> 31:59.800
The universe is expanding and we are just drifting away into an eventual heat death.

32:00.200 --> 32:02.940
It is inherently a bit nihilistic when you think about it.

32:02.940 --> 32:05.340
But in the plenum, we aren't shrapnel.

32:05.340 --> 32:08.680
We are crystals growing in a nutrient-rich solution.

32:09.220 --> 32:11.300
We are eruptions of latent potential.

32:11.860 --> 32:13.360
We are supposed to be here.

32:13.560 --> 32:16.460
We are the system realizing its own complexity.

32:16.860 --> 32:18.780
It feels almost biological.

32:19.240 --> 32:20.180
It really does.

32:20.180 --> 32:28.720
At one point, the paper even references Turing patterns, the mathematics that explains how leopards get their spots or how patterns form on seashells.

32:29.000 --> 32:33.160
This theory attempts to unify cosmology with the mathematics of biology.

32:33.680 --> 32:38.980
The universe is a living skin and galaxies are the patterns forming on that skin.

32:39.220 --> 32:41.360
And we are living inside one of those patterns.

32:41.600 --> 32:44.260
A self-organizing, self-recording crystal.

32:44.260 --> 32:45.880
It's a beautiful thought.

32:46.180 --> 32:47.900
A really beautiful thought.

32:48.320 --> 32:53.640
Whether it's true, well, that's for the telescopes and the particle accelerator to decide.

32:54.140 --> 32:58.000
But as a framework for thinking, it's incredibly powerful.

32:58.260 --> 33:03.460
At the very least, it challenges us to look at the data we already have with fresh eyes.

33:03.920 --> 33:06.380
And that really is what science is all about.

33:06.660 --> 33:10.880
Before we close, I just want to circle back one last time to that neutrino fossil registry.

33:10.880 --> 33:17.980
Because if that is real, if that is not just a mathematical convenience to solve the information problem.

33:18.300 --> 33:22.280
If it's real, it changes everything about our relationship to the past.

33:22.440 --> 33:25.000
We usually think of the past as something that's gone.

33:25.320 --> 33:26.260
It's vaporized.

33:26.380 --> 33:30.220
It only exists in our memories or in light that's traveled for billions of years.

33:30.420 --> 33:35.020
But the NFR says the past is right here, superimposed on the present.

33:35.020 --> 33:43.300
We are literally swimming through the ghosts of the last billion or trillion or however many years this plenum has existed.

33:43.800 --> 33:46.580
And if we could build a detector sensitive enough.

33:47.300 --> 33:50.180
We could watch the first stars turn on.

33:50.640 --> 33:54.000
Not by looking billions of light years away at ancient light.

33:54.240 --> 33:58.560
But by looking at the neutrinos passing through this room right here, right now.

33:59.140 --> 34:03.080
We could, in principle, play back the tape of cosmic history.

34:03.080 --> 34:06.580
It gives a whole new meaning to the phrase deep dive.

34:07.080 --> 34:08.060
Indeed it does.

34:08.320 --> 34:13.060
Fliction, whoever you are, wherever you are, you've certainly given us a lot to think about.

34:13.260 --> 34:17.920
From negative diffusion to the lattice plenum to this cosmic library.

34:18.540 --> 34:22.340
It's a heavy stack, but I think we're better for having wrestled with it.

34:22.420 --> 34:22.860
Agreed.

34:23.060 --> 34:25.540
It's good to stretch the mental muscles every once in a while.

34:25.720 --> 34:28.040
Thanks for walking us through the math and the metaphors.

34:28.040 --> 34:37.360
And to you listening, the next time you look up at the night sky, ask yourself, are you seeing the dying embers of an ancient explosion?

34:38.020 --> 34:40.960
Or are you seeing a garden growing in the dark?

34:41.120 --> 34:42.360
Something to mull over.

34:42.760 --> 34:43.600
Thanks for listening.

34:44.140 --> 34:45.960
We'll see you on the next deep dive.

34:45.960 --> 35:15.940
We'll see you on the next deep dive.

